  My answer, judged by your criterion — what's hardest to change later — is different from my value ranking, and it's worth being honest
  about that.

  Three of the four options are recomposition: the unified feed, the skill tree, and the GitHub detail pane are all UI built on abstractions
  that already exist (IncomingItem, the source registry, DetailShell). If we ship any of them wrong, we redesign a screen. Annoying, but
  cheap. Nothing about them locks us in.

  The trace-to-retrain loop is the opposite. It's where the actual irreversible commitments live, and they're mostly data contracts, not
  features:

  • The trace schema — what gets recorded when a user runs a skill (prompt, plan, execution outcome, corrections). Every trace recorded in
    the wrong shape is training data we lose or have to migrate. trace-recorder.ts exists but its format was a placeholder; the moment real
    users generate traces, that schema is load-bearing.
  • Where traces live — local-only in the workspace vs. anything server-side. That's a privacy commitment users will build trust around,
    and it also constrains how retraining can work (on-device vs. export-to-train). Retrofitting locality is nearly impossible once data
    has flowed the wrong way.
  • Adapter identity and versioning — right now a skill points at one adapter URL. Once users have trained/equipped state persisted in
    their workspace exports, changing how adapters are named and versioned means migrations forever. Same class of problem as the vault
    export format, which is already on v2.

